<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-600-596  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 600 596.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  August 15 1989 v3 n30 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Host apps get Mitem face lift. (MitemView software applicationsdevelopment tool) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Battelle, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Mitem Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   MitemView (Program development software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSoftware DesignProgram Development ToolsApplications Programming.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John BattelleandM;Boston -- Mitem Corp. last week introduced MitemView, a software developmenttool that marries mainframe and minicomputer applications to aHyperCard-based graphical interface.andM;Unlike MacWorkStation, Apple's solution for connecting host applications to aMac-like interface, MitemView does not require modification of the host-basedapplication's code.andM;&quot;We want to use Macs for an executive information system but don't want tochange host code,&quot; said Jim Young, assistant to the chairman of ElectronicData Systems in Dallas.andP;  &quot;This will let us use Macs to access hostapplications already built.&quot;andM;Transparently to the user, MitemView's independent real-time operating systemroutes messages between the host and HyperCard.andP;  The host continues to sendmessages as if a terminal were attached, but MitemView translates the hostcommands to HyperCard and sends the user's input to the host.andP;  The userinterface is stored as a HyperCard stack, and external commands (XCMDs)monitor messages between the Mitem software and the HyperCard interface.andM;MitemView works on any Mac with at least 2 Mbytes of RAM.andP;  It will ship inSeptember for $995.andM;Mitem Corp. is located at 2105 Hamilton Ave., Suite 190, San Jose, Calif.andO;95125; (408) 559-8801.andO;</TEXT></DOC>